[1] Pandemic continues
Date: Tue 26 Oct 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/10/who-advisors-say-covid-19-pandemic-far-over


After reviewing the latest COVID-19 developments last week, the World Health Organization (WHO) emergency committee said the pandemic is far from over, though countries are making progress in rolling out vaccines and treatments. The group of outside advisors met on 22 Oct 2021 by video conference for the 9th time and unanimously agreed that the situation still warrants a public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC), which was declared on 30 Jan 2020. The group typically meets every 3 months or more often as needed.

In a statement released today [26 Oct 2021] on its deliberations, the group raised concerns about Africa's challenges in accessing enough vaccines, tests, and treatments and in monitoring COVID-19 spread, given that many countries have gaps in lab capacity and genomic sequencing (https://bit.ly/3vQCTwh).

The committee also said there's a critical need for all countries to use all tools at their disposal to ease the pandemic's many impacts. Committee members modified and extended most of their temporary recommendations but added a new one that supports uptake of WHO-recommended treatments by addressing access and affordability.

More global headlines
---------------------
- An independent monitoring board set up by the WHO and the World Bank in 2018 to track the world's outbreak and emergency readiness in the wake of West Africa's Ebola outbreak detailed the failures in the world's response to the COVID-19 pandemic. The Global Preparedness Monitoring Board -- in its new report -- said the failures stemmed from inequality and inaction and were worsened by political division. It called for new efforts to address future threats, including an international agreement on health preparedness and a global summit of health leaders to tackle the topic (https://www.gpmb.org/annual-reports/annual-report-2021).

- In vaccine developments, the Germany-based BioNTech, which developed the mRNA vaccine marketed by Pfizer, said today [26 Oct 2021] that it will build a vaccine production facility in Rwanda next year (https://investors.biontech.de/news-releases/news-release-details/biontech-plans-initiate-construction-mrna-vaccine-manufacturing), the European Medicines Agency (EMA) approved the Moderna booster ([Spikevax]; https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/news/spikevax-ema-recommendation-booster), and China signaled that it will begin vaccinating children as young as 3 years old (https://apnews.com/article/coronavirus-pandemic-lifestyle-business-beijing-travel-4680b533429a7e3e75c6f99745b3664b [see comment below]).

- Meanwhile, in outbreak developments, the Chinese city of Lanzhou -- the capital of Gansu province and home to 4 million people -- is on lockdown after 6 local cases were detected, according to The Guardian (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/oct/26/china-locks-down-city-lanzhou-gansu-covid).

- In Europe, Russia and Ukraine -- 2 eastern European countries battling COVID-19 surges -- reported record daily highs for deaths today [26 Oct 2021] (Russia: https://www.reuters.com/world/russia-puts-onus-regional-leaders-step-up-covid-fight-2021-10-26/ and Ukraine: https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-ukraine-deaths/ukraine-urges-citizens-to-get-vaccinated-as-covid-19-toll-hits-new-record-idUSKBN2HG1KB).

- The global total today [26 Oct 2021] climbed to 244 318 680 cases, with 4 960 323 deaths, according to the Johns Hopkins online dashboard (https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/).

[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

